<dl id="n25174h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25174h">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25174h"> 174(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> blueyed dusky nigger betwn / dark Eur. barb / hair curly with heat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As regards colour, it is not only indisputable that men are blackest on the equator and fairest in extreme north&mdash;which points to the heat of the sun as the main cause of difference&mdash;but (as Darwin has shown in detail) the young of man, like the young of other animals, tend to revert to the colour of the remote ancestor; and while the babes of Europeans are darker, and those of the yellow and red races fairer than the adults, <mark>the negro baby is less black, and has blue eyes, with a dusky</mark> skin <mark>scarcely darker in colour than that of some Aryan infants</mark>. The shape of the head also seems to tend to extremes under hard conditions of life, and the <mark>hair becomes more curly in hot</mark> damp climates, and straighter in cold countries. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 50</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14117l" href="c14all.htm#c14117l">VI.C.14:117(l)</a>, <a name="c14118b" href="c14all.htm#c14118b">VI.C.14:118(b)</a>, <a name="c14118c" href="c14all.htm#c14118c">VI.C.14:118(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
